Sonar is flagging the three tests because they execute the same logic and differ only by the bearer-token value.

Replace these three tests:

* `shouldCreateApiClientWithBearerToken`
* `shouldCreateApiClientWhenBearerTokenIsBlank`
* `shouldCreateApiClientWhenBearerTokenIsNull`

with one parameterized test.

```java
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertNotNull;

import org.junit.jupiter.params.ParameterizedTest;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.provider.NullSource;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.provider.ValueSource;
```

```java
@ParameterizedTest(name = "should create API client when bearer token is [{0}]")
@NullSource
@ValueSource(strings = {
        "",
        " ",
        "test-token"
})
void shouldCreateApiClientForBearerToken(String bearerToken) {
    PingScimProperties properties = properties(
            "https://ping.example.com",
            bearerToken
    );

    ApiClient result =
            configuration.pingApiClient(properties);

    assertNotNull(result);
    assertEquals(
            "https://ping.example.com",
            result.getBasePath()
    );
}
```

Keep the API-bean test separately because it tests different behavior:

```java
