Your final test class can look like this:

```java
class PingClientConfigurationTest {

    private PingClientConfiguration configuration;

    @BeforeEach
    void setUp() {
        configuration = new PingClientConfiguration();
    }

    @ParameterizedTest(
            name = "should create API client for bearer token [{0}]"
    )
    @NullSource
    @ValueSource(strings = {
            "",
            " ",
            "test-token"
    })
    void shouldCreateApiClientForBearerToken(
            String bearerToken
    ) {
        PingScimProperties properties = properties(
                "https://ping.example.com",
                bearerToken
        );

        ApiClient result =
                configuration.pingApiClient(properties);

        assertNotNull(result);
        assertEquals(
                "https://ping.example.com",
                result.getBasePath()
        );
    }

    @Test
    void shouldCreatePartnersResourceTypeApi() {
        ApiClient apiClient = new ApiClient();

        PartnersBeAp74737ResourceTypeApi result =
                configuration
                        .partnersBeAp74737ResourceTypeApi(
                                apiClient
                        );

        assertNotNull(result);
    }

    private PingScimProperties properties(
            String baseUrl,
            String bearerToken
    ) {
        return new PingScimProperties(
                true,
                baseUrl,
                null,
                null,
                bearerToken,
                Duration.ofSeconds(5),
                Duration.ofSeconds(10)
        );
    }
}
```

This resolves the Sonar duplication issue while still covering all branches:

* `bearerToken == null`
* empty token
* whitespace-only token
* valid token.
